a ulla vateri a ullovateric papilla vateri vater papilla vater a ulla peria ull* peri a ull* choledoch* alcholedoch* bile duct* biliary cholangio* gall duct duoden* small bowel small intestin* enter* pancrea* A ulla of Vater su Surgery carcin* cancer* neoplas* tumour* tum cyst* growth* adenocarcin* malign* Duodenal Neoplasms su Surgery Pancreatic Neoplasms su Surgery Common Bile Duct Neoplasms su Surgery surger* surgical* operat* resection* preoperative Surgical Procedures Operative General Surgery pancreatect* pancreaticojejunost* pancreaticogastros* pancreaticoduodenect* duodenopancreatectom* pancreato biliary pancreatectomy pancreaticoduodenectomy pancreaticojejunostomy PET MRI NMRI zeugmatogra* emission positron magneti* MR NMR proton acoustic ARFI tomogra* scan scans imaging Positron Emission Tomography Magnetic Resonance Imaging Endosonography endosonogra* EUS echogra* ultrason* ultrasound Ultrasonography endoscop* Endoscopy sensitiv diagnos limit to ed [Clinical study of the imaging validity in detecting infiltration of the mesenteric-portal axis in pancreatic carcinoma].The authors examine the value of different imaging techniques (CT, MRI) in the diagnosis of the involvement of the mesenteric-portal vessels in the pancreatic cancer. In 20 jaundiced patients they obtained in all cases a correct diagnosis about the etiology of the jaundice. The correspondence of the preoperative imaging study with the involvement of the mesenteric-portal vessels was respectively 73% for the CT and 78% for the MRI. In all cases the intra-operative echography allowed a correct diagnosis of the vascular involvement.